Therefore, the sensitivity of the cell line to cetuximab is expected to be determined by other factors, such as the presence of the EGFR ligands and the signaling pathways downstream of EGFR. In general, Cetuximab is used to treat metastatic colorectal cancer and metastatic squamous cell carcinoma of the head and neck. It is also used in combination with radiation therapy for locally advanced rectal cancer. Cetuximab is an IgG1 monoclonal antibody that inhibits the EGFR, resulting in cell cycle arrest and apoptosis. It is thought to work by blocking the binding of EGFR ligands to the receptor, preventing the activation of downstream signaling pathways. However, the exact mechanism of action may vary depending on the specific context of the tumor microenvironment. In the absence of EGFR mutations, the presence of EGFR ligands and the downstream signaling pathways are the primary determinants of cetuximab sensitivity. In this case, the absence of EGFR mutations and the presence of other mutations, such as ARAF, BTK, DOT1L, EGFR, ETV5, FLT1, MTOR, NPM1, SMARCA4, TP53, suggest that the cell line may be sensitive to cetuximab. However, further investigation is needed to confirm this.
